It remains to notice certain clauses which were sometimes inserted iu the formula at the instance of the defendant, viz. exceptiones and praescriptiones pro reo. It was a peculiar rule of the formulary system that the defendant was not allowed to plead some grounds of defence in iudicio unless they had been alleged in iure, and the judge’s attention expressly called to them by an addition to the formula. Exceptiones are pleas of this character: delences which do not actually traverse the allegation of the plaintiff, but set up a countervailing right, rendering the former of at least no present value, and which, if they are to be successfully pleaded, require (though to a larger extent in some classes of actions than in others) to·be tersely embadied in the formula, by an addition to the intentio, instructing the iudex to condemn the defendant only on the fullilment of two conditions instead, as usual, of one, viz.
